    "narrative": "The projected landscape for LawDog today highlights **Lawrence Butler** and **Daulton Varsho** as our premier offensive engines. **Lawrence Butler** carries the highest score of the day (74.56) due to an excellent matchup against Michael Wacha; even assuming a bottom-third batting order, his combination of favorable park factors and the +15% SP skill adjustment makes him a mandatory start. Similarly, **Daulton Varsho** benefits significantly from the matchup against Bello, capitalizing on a +13% SP skill bump and a park factor that favors his power profile, pushing his efficiency score to a strong 68.40. **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** remains a core anchor, providing a steady 66.29 floor thanks to his high base projection and a slight boost from the slow delivery of the opposing pitcher, which may create opportunities for his rare, high-value stolen base attempts.\n\nRegarding our bench decisions, **Luis Arraez** was the hardest omission, finishing just shy of the cutoff with a 41.94 score. While **Luis Arraez** typically provides high-floor batting average support, his negative platoon adjustment against S\u00e1nchez, combined with the 40% rain risk, suppressed his upside compared to the higher-scoring profiles of **Cal Raleigh** and **Jonathan Aranda**. We are also monitoring the status of **Matt Chapman**, who sits at 42.48. Although **Matt Chapman** is currently active in the lineup, he shares the same weather-impacted matchup as the benched **Luis Arraez** and **Jung Hoo Lee**; should the rain risk escalate, we will be forced to pivot to our bench depth. **Masyn Winn** rounds out the lineup with a marginal 42.64, holding his spot purely because the wind projection provides enough of a boost to keep him above the 40.0 \"Below Floor\" threshold, though he remains a candidate for mid-game substitution if the efficiency of his plate appearances lags.",
